results.notes:
Growing gregariously in small but tight clusters at the base of a mature basswood tree (likely the European T. cordata). No other potential hosts nearby. I have never seen these mushrooms here before. Incidentally, this is the same spot where A. phalloides of obs 188196 was collected 4 years ago almost to the day; it’s been growing here every year, including 2018.
I usually don’t bother with corts. I only picked these in hopes of putting a name because of the unusual mycorrhizal association. Otherwise, identification of a violet-brown capped cort from subgenus Phlegmacium looked like a certain and quick dead end to me.
A lucky Google search “Cortinarius growing with Tilia” led me to Mycowalt’s obs 112094, where a relationship with basswood was mentioned by Irene Andersson. A further look online for C. balteatocumitilis suggested this could be it. I understand there are other similar-looking taxa with names beginning with “balteato-”.
Didn’t save this particular collection because the mushrooms were found uprooted a day or two ago by people or squirrels. Was hoping to get a fresh and more mature voucher later, though it’s been rather cold and rainy and they were not in a hurry to get any bigger.

results.notes:
More mature fruiting bodies picked fresh from a fruiting mentioned in obs 344736. Very dense and heavy for their size. Probably still too young to drop spores. There are more of these still around, trying to grow in what’s left of this season. I hope they can make it despite the cold nights and chilly days and yet another round of soaking rain coming their way…

DNA Sequencing Results & Discussion:
A clean and contiguous nrDNA sequence of 726 bps was obtained from this material by Dr. Kudzma and uploaded to the observation. It consists of the last 46 characters of nrSSU, followed by the full-length nrITS sequence of 593 bps and then by the first 87 nucleotides of nrLSU. The nrITS sequence is a full consensus, meaning that each read delivers the entire ITS region, and the two are 100% identical. There are no ambiguous positions, it’s a single haplotype.
The ITS sequences is a 100% match to the published accessions of the holotypes of the following taxa: C. balteatus var. praestantoides and C. veneris. The previous name for this taxon – C. balteatocumatilis Rob. Henry ex P.D. Orton – is apparently a deprecated synonym. Liimatainen et al. don’t discuss why C. flavescentipes is the preferred name.
